<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-10-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-10-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="179" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d179">
                            <head><persName type="from">S. Price Edwards, esq., collector of
                                    customs, Liverpool,</persName> to <persName type="to">Laird
                                    Brothers</persName>.</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Custom-House,
                                        Liverpool,</hi></placeName>
                                    <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-10-27"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 27, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Gentlemen:</hi> I hereby beg to inform you that
                                your two cupola vessels are now detained, under the 223d section of
                                “the customs consolidated act,” the ground of detention being a
                                violation of “the foreign enlistment act.” And I take leave further
                                to state that the officers in charge have received directions to
                                remove your workman at once from on board the ships.</p>
                            <p>I am, gentlemen, your obedient servant,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>S. PRICE EDWARDS, <hi rend="italic">Collector.</hi></signed></closer>
                            <postscript>
                                <p>Messrs. <hi rend="smallcaps">Laird Brothers,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Birkenhead.</hi></p>
                            </postscript>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>